# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1890-cleveland-spiders-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1888-cleveland-blues-season] The **1888 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 50–82 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] Before the 1889 season, the Cleveland Blues switched from the American Association to the National League.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They also earned a new nickname, the **Cleveland Spiders**, because so many of their players were very thin.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished their first season in the National League with a 61–72 record, good enough for sixth place.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-baltimore-orioles-season] The **Baltimore Orioles** team left the American Association after the 1889 season and started playing in the minor Atlantic Association.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-baltimore-orioles-season] However, when the Brooklyn Gladiators ballclub folded mid-way through the 1890 season, the Orioles returned to the AA to finish out the season.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1890 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 20th season of the franchise.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-boston-reds-season] The **1890 Boston Reds** baseball team was a member of the short-lived Players' League.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-boston-reds-season] They compiled an 81–47 record and won the league championship.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-boston-reds-season] After the season, the league folded, but the Reds were invited to join the American Association for the following season and folded after a single season with players dispersed to other AA teams.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] The **1890 Brooklyn Bridegrooms** left the American Association and joined the National League.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] They won the league championship, becoming one of a select few teams to win championships in different leagues in back-to-back seasons.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] In the 1890 World Series, the Bridegrooms faced the American Association Champions, the Louisville Colonels.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1890 Cleveland Spiders** finished with a 44–88 record and a seventh-place finish in the National League.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The team played six straight home games in Indianapolis, Indiana at Indianapolis Park between July 28 and August 2 against the Brooklyn Bridegrooms and New York Giants.
[src:1890-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] It was a former Sunday-games ballpark of the Indianapolis Hoosiers who had folded at the end of the previous season.
